<subsection xml:id="subsec-properties-of-symmetry-and-reflection" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Properties of Symmetry and Reflection</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_czieynx3">
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_gvsgizye">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8yq70ic1">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.2 Reflection and Congruence
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0w5xzkam">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Identify lines of symmetry in plane figures
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_wg3lj8xy" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qncqn9wq" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p>
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_6c47axpd">
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that symmetry means an object looks exactly identical on both sides when folded, flipped, rotated, or reflected. Understand that a line of symmetry divides a shape into two identical halves where one half is the mirror image of the other.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_n29chl4n">
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Identify lines of symmetry in plane figures by folding, drawing, and visual inspection. Determine the number of lines of symmetry for regular polygons, letters, and everyday objects.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_9t5zlhie">
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Recognise and identify lines of symmetry in real-world objects, classroom items, and everyday situations involving reflection and congruence.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/reflection-and-congruence/properties-of-symmetry-and-reflection.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/reflection-and-congruence/step-by-step-guide_properties-of-symmetry-and-reflection.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <!-- <p>
      <term>Reflection</term> is the mirror image of an object over a line (line of reflection)
    </p> -->
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Paper Folding Exploration (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Groups
        </p>
        <p>
            Give each group a square piece of paper labelled ABCD.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 1:</alert> Fold the square in half from left to right so that corner <m>A</m> aligns with corner <m>B</m> and corner <m>D</m> aligns with corner <m>C</m>. Unfold and mark the fold line as <m>XY</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 2:</alert> Fold the square in half from top to bottom so that corner <m>D</m> aligns with corner <m>A</m> and corner <m>C</m> aligns with corner <m>B</m>. Unfold and mark the fold line as <m>RS</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 3:</alert> Fold the paper diagonally from corner <m>A</m> to corner <m>C</m>. Unfold and trace the fold line along <m>BD</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Step 4:</alert> Fold the paper diagonally from corner <m>D</m> to corner <m>B</m>. Unfold and trace the fold line along <m>AC</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Questions:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_95tqvdcs"><q>How many fold lines did you create?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_wylsaix3"><q>What do you notice about the two halves on each side of a fold line?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tbtn92a8"><q>Are all fold lines the same type?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_e8h1ivl5"><q>Try the same process with a rectangle. What do you notice?</q></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <activity xml:id="auto_hc4hpj0k">
      <statement>
        <p>
        <term>Work in groups</term>
      </p>
        <p>
          Exploring reflections with mirrors.
        </p>
        <p>
          <term>Needed Materials</term>
        </p>
        <p>
          <ul xml:id="auto_8wxa5qxs">
            <li xml:id="auto_0ijaa5p6">
              <p>
                A small mirror.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_tuw7s92z">
              <p>
                Marker or pencil.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_pnm16yhw">
              <p>
                Piece of paper.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
          <term>Steps.</term>
        </p>
        <p>
          <ul xml:id="auto_tz0tso0l">
            <li xml:id="auto_lvw2o4ws">
              <p>
                Hold your hand about <m>10 \, cm</m> in front of the mirror, with your palm facing the mirror.
                 What do you notice?
              </p>
              <image source="Reflection-hand.jpg" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>Hand</shortdescription>
              </image>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_twwwg7sz">
              <p>
                Turn your hand so that the back of your hand faces the mirror instead. Observe again. 
                How does the reflection mimic the shape of your hand? Is there symmetry between your hand and its relection?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_0vatlyyo">
              <p>
                Hold your hand in front of the mirror with your palm facing the mirror, then fold your fingers to make a fist.
                 Does the reflection mimic your hand movements in the same direction?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_dxuf04v6">
              <p>
                Slowly rotate your hand in different directions (up, down, sideways) while watching the mirror. 
                Discuss how the mirror's reflection always mirrors the real movement.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_s96khm9x">
              <p>
                Move your hand closer to the mirror until it touches the mirror. What do you notice?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
          <term>Key Takeaway</term>
        </p>
        <p>
          <ul xml:id="auto_xu8cd6rp">
            <li xml:id="auto_ufdjt2sq">
              <p>
                The mirror does not create a random image but produces a reversed copy of the object in front of it. 
                From your activity, you will notice that when you hold your right hand in front of the mirror, the 
                reflection is a reverse which appers as the left hand. This phenomena is called <term>lateral inversion.</term>
                 Lateral inversion is when a reflected object appears to be flipped along a vertical axis. 
              </p>
            </li>
              <li xml:id="auto_jdgfnjp2">
              <p>
                You will also notice that the reflection mimics you hand movements when you flip, rotate it and when you fold it.
              </p>
            </li>
              <li xml:id="auto_usjs28h3">
              <p>
                As you move your hand closer to the mirror, you notice that the distance between reflection and the mirror
                 reduces. When you touch the mirror, the image appears to touch your hand. Your hand and its reflection are in symmetry.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="auto_tfcmhgw5">
      
      <p>
        From a piece of paper, cut out a square shape and label it as shown below.
      </p>

      <image width="50%">
        <shortdescription>Square</shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="original-square-1">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[blue,thick](0,0)coordinate(A)--(4,0)coordinate(B)--(4,4)coordinate(C)
            --(0,4)coordinate(D)--(0,0)coordinate(A);
            \node at (-.1,0){A};
            \node at (4.1,0){B};
            \node at (4.1,4.1){C};
            \node at (-.1,4.1){D};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p>
        Fold the square in half from left to right such that the corner <m>A</m> aligns with corner <m>B</m> and
         corner <m>D</m> aligns with corner <m>C.</m> This will create a rectangle.
      </p>
      <p>
        Unfold the paper and make a dotted line across the fold line and label it as <m>XY</m> as shown. 
      </p>

      <image width="50%">
        <shortdescription>Square</shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="square-2">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[blue,thick](0,0)coordinate(A)--(4,0)coordinate(B)--(4,4)coordinate(C)
            --(0,4)coordinate(D)--(0,0)coordinate(A);
            \draw[style=dashed,color=red](2,4)--(2,0);
            \node at (-.1,0){A};
            \node at (4.1,0){B};
            \node at (4.1,4.1){C};
            \node at (-.1,4.1){D};
            \node at (2,-.1){Y};
            \node at (2,4.1){X};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p>
        Notice that the left side of the line <m>XY</m> and the right side are exacly the same/ identical.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now, fold the square in half from the top to the bottom such that the corner <m>D</m> aligns with corner <m>A</m> and
         corner <m>C</m> aligns with corner <m>B.</m> This will create another rectangle.
      </p>
      <p>
        Unfold the paper and make a dotted line across the second fold line and label it as <m>RS</m> as shown. 
      </p>

      <image width="50%">
        <shortdescription>Square</shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="square-3">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[blue,thick](0,0)coordinate(A)--(4,0)coordinate(B)--(4,4)coordinate(C)
            --(0,4)coordinate(D)--(0,0)coordinate(A);
            \draw[style=dashed,color=red](2,4)--(2,0);
            \draw[style=dashed,color=green](0,2)--(4,2);
            \node at (-.1,0){A};
            \node at (4.1,0){B};
            \node at (4.1,4.1){C};
            \node at (-.1,4.1){D};
            \node at (2,-.1){Y};
            \node at (2,4.1){X};
            \node at (-.1,2){R};
            \node at (4.1,2){S};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p>
        Again, you notice that the upper side of the line <m>RS</m> and the lower side are exacly the same/ identical.
      </p>
      <p>
        Next, fold the paper in half from the bottom left corner <m>A</m> to the top right corner <m>C.</m>
        This creates a triangle.
      </p>
      <p>
        Unfold the paper, you will notice that a fold line appears along <m>BD.</m> Trace a dotted line along 
        the fold line as showm.
      </p>

      <image width="50%">
        <shortdescription>Square</shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="square-4">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[blue,thick](0,0)coordinate(A)--(4,0)coordinate(B)--(4,4)coordinate(C)
            --(0,4)coordinate(D)--(0,0)coordinate(A);
            \draw[style=dashed,color=red](2,4)--(2,0);
            \draw[style=dashed,color=green](0,2)--(4,2);
            \draw[style=dashed,color=yellow](0,4)--(4,0);
            \node at (-.1,0){A};
            \node at (4.1,0){B};
            \node at (4.1,4.1){C};
            \node at (-.1,4.1){D};
            \node at (2,-.1){Y};
            \node at (2,4.1){X};
            \node at (-.1,2){R};
            \node at (4.1,2){S};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p>
        Finally, fold the paper in half from the top left corner <m>D</m> to the bottom right corner <m>B.</m>
        This creates another triangle.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now, unfold the paper, you will notice that a fold line appears along <m>AC.</m> Trace a dotted line along 
        the fold line as showm.
      </p>

      <image width="50%">
        <shortdescription>Square</shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="square-5">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[blue,thick](0,0)coordinate(A)--(4,0)coordinate(B)--(4,4)coordinate(C)
            --(0,4)coordinate(D)--(0,0)coordinate(A);
            \draw[style=dashed,color=red](2,4)--(2,0);
            \draw[style=dashed,color=green](0,2)--(4,2);
            \draw[style=dashed,color=yellow](0,4)--(4,0);
            \draw[style=dashed,color=purple](0,0)--(4,4);
