    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment (5 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Q1:</alert> How many lines of symmetry are there among all 26 uppercase alphabet letters? (See answer table in Phase 3.)
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q2:</alert> Draw 5 objects and show their lines of symmetry.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q3:</alert> A regular hexagon has how many lines of symmetry? Draw and label them.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q4:</alert> Explain why a rectangle has 2 lines of symmetry, not 4.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q5:</alert> Design a logo that has exactly 3 lines of symmetry.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer Key:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_ind3epj3"><alert>Q1:</alert> See the alphabet symmetry table in Phase 3.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4zfvywgu"><alert>Q2:</alert> Examples — door (<m>1</m> line), window (<m>2</m> lines), clock (<m>12</m> lines), table (<m>2</m> lines), pencil (<m>1</m> line).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_60nblkdu"><alert>Q3:</alert> A regular hexagon has <m>6</m> lines of symmetry — <m>3</m> vertex-to-vertex and <m>3</m> midpoint-to-midpoint.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xhp66x8t"><alert>Q4:</alert> The diagonals of a rectangle do not create mirror-image halves, so only the horizontal and vertical centre lines are lines of symmetry.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ovzxdpu1"><alert>Q5:</alert> A logo based on an equilateral triangle has exactly <m>3</m> lines of symmetry.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-plane-of-symmetry">

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Identify fruits and vegetables that have only 2 planes of symmetry.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            One example is a (curved) banana. When you cut a banana vertically down the middle, you create a plane of symmetry. When you cut a banana horizontally along the banana, you create another plane of symmetry. Therefore, a banana has 2 planes of symmetry.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

      <exercise>
      <p>
        Identify lines of symmetry in the alphabetical letters below
      </p>
      
